67
00:05:06.100 --> 00:05:09.100
And when you zoom in, you can already see

68
00:05:09.100 --> 00:05:12.140
considerably more — more granularity

69
00:05:12.140 --> 00:05:14.140
and considerably more wind.

70
00:05:14.140 --> 00:05:16.140
Try it, make it a bit clearer.

71
00:05:48.380 --> 00:05:51.380
I haven't had such good experience

72
00:05:51.380 --> 00:05:53.380
with rain and thunderstorm,

73
00:05:53.380 --> 00:05:58.380
or precipitation in general added in.

74
00:05:58.380 --> 00:06:01.380
I have to be honest,

75
00:06:01.380 --> 00:06:05.600
I haven't really seen it bring particularly good forecasts

76
00:06:05.600 --> 00:06:09.600
for Switzerland specifically.

77
00:06:09.600 --> 00:06:12.600
What's centrally important on Windy

78
00:06:12.600 --> 00:06:15.600
is actually wind.

79
00:06:15.600 --> 00:06:18.980
Now and then, especially abroad,

80
00:06:18.980 --> 00:06:20.980
also clouds.

81
00:06:20.980 --> 00:06:23.980
And the second most important thing on Windy

82
00:06:23.980 --> 00:06:27.050
is definitely temperature.

83
00:06:27.050 --> 00:06:29.050
That's a cool example,

84
00:06:29.050 --> 00:06:32.050
especially today regarding Foehn maybe,

85
00:06:32.050 --> 00:06:34.050
in trickier situations,

86
00:06:34.050 --> 00:06:38.050
when it's less than 4 hectopascals,

87
00:06:38.050 --> 00:06:40.050
to be able to read it off

88
00:06:40.050 --> 00:06:45.050
by the temperature gradient between south,

89
00:06:45.050 --> 00:06:48.050
the main Alpine ridge and north.

90
00:06:48.050 --> 00:06:52.240
And always so that you can really read a proper

91
00:06:52.240 --> 00:06:54.240
temperature gradient,

92
00:06:54.240 --> 00:06:56.240
always set the altitude accordingly,

93
00:06:56.240 --> 00:06:58.240
if you set this here on the right,

94
00:06:58.240 --> 00:07:02.240
set the altitude to about 1000 metres.

95
00:07:02.240 --> 00:07:05.780
And then for example you can see very well

96
00:07:05.780 --> 00:07:08.910
the temperature gradient there

97
00:07:08.910 --> 00:07:11.910
and I've actually had it work really

98
00:07:11.910 --> 00:07:13.910
very strongly as well.

99
00:07:13.910 --> 00:07:14.910
So as I was saying,

100
00:07:14.910 --> 00:07:18.910
you can adjust the altitude here,

101
00:07:18.910 --> 00:07:20.910
also for the respective wind,

102
00:07:20.910 --> 00:07:23.910
for example, where you can choose,

103
00:07:23.910 --> 00:07:27.260
of course that's very useful for us.

104
00:07:27.260 --> 00:07:28.260
Very good.

105
00:07:28.260 --> 00:07:30.260
We can go significantly higher

106
00:07:30.260 --> 00:07:33.260
and zoom out a bit more.

107
00:07:33.260 --> 00:07:37.260
It's clear that it deals with all elevations.

108
00:07:37.260 --> 00:07:39.260
And you can really easily

109
00:07:39.260 --> 00:07:41.260
spot strong wind bands,

110
00:07:41.260 --> 00:07:43.260
if you now go to

111
00:07:43.260 --> 00:07:45.970
a lower altitude,

112
00:07:45.970 --> 00:07:47.970
where it gets a bit more interesting.

113
00:07:47.970 --> 00:07:50.420
But maybe at 1000 metres once,

114
00:07:50.420 --> 00:07:52.420
and then with one glance

115
00:07:52.420 --> 00:07:56.420
you can spot wind very well on Windy.

116
00:07:56.420 --> 00:07:59.510
So now this is the wind,

117
00:07:59.510 --> 00:08:01.510
maybe in our area

118
00:08:01.510 --> 00:08:03.510
and where I notice

119
00:08:03.510 --> 00:08:05.510
the stronger wind band.

120
00:08:05.510 --> 00:08:08.510
Is it nearby and worth

121
00:08:08.510 --> 00:08:10.510
or do you see here,

122
00:08:10.510 --> 00:08:11.510
looking,

123
00:08:11.510 --> 00:08:13.510
or note well,

124
00:08:13.510 --> 00:08:15.510
also at a low altitude of 1000,

125
00:08:15.510 --> 00:08:16.510
just under 1000 metres.

126
00:08:16.510 --> 00:08:18.510
Yeah, on the Plateau,

127
00:08:18.510 --> 00:08:19.510
right?

128
00:08:19.510 --> 00:08:21.510
So Windy for me

129
00:08:21.510 --> 00:08:25.150
is actually already

130
00:08:25.150 --> 00:08:27.150
a quite special display,

131
00:08:27.150 --> 00:08:29.150
if you can really very broadly

132
00:08:29.150 --> 00:08:31.280
see,

133
00:08:31.280 --> 00:08:35.470
where there's less wind.

134
00:08:35.470 --> 00:08:37.470
So I find it really neat,

135
00:08:37.470 --> 00:08:39.470
and then it makes exactly that

136
00:08:39.470 --> 00:08:42.080
very visible.

137
00:08:42.080 --> 00:08:44.080
We also have

138
00:08:44.080 --> 00:08:46.080
the option

139
00:08:46.080 --> 00:08:50.620
to choose different weather models.

140
00:08:50.620 --> 00:08:54.620
We have for example the option

141
00:08:54.620 --> 00:08:58.620
to fade in city labels at the same time,

142
00:08:58.620 --> 00:09:00.620
though that won't do much.

143
00:09:00.620 --> 00:09:05.330
You can also have wind shown with direction

144
00:09:05.330 --> 00:09:12.970
and especially with strength labelled.

145
00:09:12.970 --> 00:09:15.970
But I'll make it

146
00:09:15.970 --> 00:09:17.970
a bit cleaner again later,

147
00:09:17.970 --> 00:09:19.970
because at the beginning

148
00:09:19.970 --> 00:09:23.970
I always bring in very little general information.

149
00:09:23.970 --> 00:09:26.970
What I've pre-set

150
00:09:26.970 --> 00:09:28.970
to be permanently on

151
00:09:28.970 --> 00:09:30.970
is the particle animation.

152
00:09:30.970 --> 00:09:31.970
I think

153
00:09:31.970 --> 00:09:33.970
that's the case for most of you,

154
00:09:33.970 --> 00:09:36.970
but what you can also enable,

155
00:09:36.970 --> 00:09:39.970
from my point of view sensibly,

156
00:09:39.970 --> 00:09:41.970
are the isobars,

157
00:09:41.970 --> 00:09:44.970
the lines of equal pressure.

158
00:09:44.970 --> 00:09:47.970
And you can already read a lot from those.

159
00:09:47.970 --> 00:09:49.970
And the cool thing,

160
00:09:49.970 --> 00:09:51.970
down there with the date.

161
00:09:51.970 --> 00:09:54.970
Alongside that, you can also look a bit ahead

162
00:09:54.970 --> 00:09:55.970
and trust

163
00:09:55.970 --> 00:10:00.970
how highs and lows will shift generally.

164
00:10:00.970 --> 00:10:02.970
So I find that pretty neat.

165
00:10:02.970 --> 00:10:07.480
You can really look far ahead,

166
00:10:07.480 --> 00:10:10.480
get a sense of the whole picture for somewhere else.

167
00:10:10.480 --> 00:10:12.480
That said though,

168
00:10:12.480 --> 00:10:15.480
I wouldn't take it at face value,

169
00:10:15.480 --> 00:10:18.480
anything more than three days out.

170
00:10:18.480 --> 00:10:22.480
It's pure speculation for me, in that range.

171
00:10:22.480 --> 00:10:26.480
But certainly good to have, from my point of view,

172
00:10:26.480 --> 00:10:28.480
let's free that up,

173
00:10:28.480 --> 00:10:29.480
the isobars,

174
00:10:29.480 --> 00:10:33.020
I have those set on permanently.

175
00:10:33.020 --> 00:10:35.020
And depending on the model,

176
00:10:35.020 --> 00:10:38.020
there are different weather models.

177
00:10:38.020 --> 00:10:42.270
You can also see

178
00:10:42.270 --> 00:10:45.270
when they're updated,

179
00:10:45.270 --> 00:10:50.270
you'd have to click the info button for that.

180
00:10:50.270 --> 00:10:53.270
Then we have the respective models

181
00:10:53.270 --> 00:10:56.270
with the grid that's being computed —

182
00:10:56.270 --> 00:10:59.270
9 km grid, European model.

183
00:10:59.270 --> 00:11:03.270
And then the whole thing is also updated,

184
00:11:03.270 --> 00:11:06.270
at the corresponding interval.

185
00:11:06.270 --> 00:11:10.460
Which is actually not bad,

186
00:11:10.460 --> 00:11:14.460
the interval — then it's also,

187
00:11:14.460 --> 00:11:19.460
okay, in about 13 hours the next update comes.

188
00:11:19.460 --> 00:11:22.460
That means it doesn't really make sense

189
00:11:22.460 --> 00:11:24.460
to check in every few minutes.

190
00:11:24.460 --> 00:11:26.460
My conclusion,

191
00:11:26.460 --> 00:11:29.460
is to spread that out a few times over the day,

192
00:11:29.460 --> 00:11:31.460
spread out.

193
00:11:31.460 --> 00:11:34.560
And take the info from there,

194
00:11:34.560 --> 00:11:37.560
if we now go in there,

195
00:11:37.560 --> 00:11:41.560
this one's coming nicely from the German Weather Service,

196
00:11:41.560 --> 00:11:45.560
but it goes for all three bits.

197
00:11:45.560 --> 00:11:47.560
And updated

198
00:11:47.560 --> 00:11:50.560
at significantly shorter intervals.

199
00:11:50.560 --> 00:11:52.560
But you might already notice,

200
00:11:52.560 --> 00:11:57.560
the German model also doesn't cover such a large area,

201
00:11:57.560 --> 00:12:00.560
if you're travelling somewhere else especially.

202
00:12:00.560 --> 00:12:05.560
The European model with the 3.3 km grid doesn't.

203
00:12:05.560 --> 00:12:08.560
Then you have to go a bit

204
00:12:08.560 --> 00:12:10.560
larger again,

205
00:12:10.560 --> 00:12:14.590
ICON EU with 3 km,

206
00:12:14.590 --> 00:12:18.980
or with 3 km.

207
00:12:18.980 --> 00:12:21.980
So those are the models.

208
00:12:21.980 --> 00:12:25.980
I personally work at the start

209
00:12:25.980 --> 00:12:41.750
to get an

210
00:12:41.750 --> 00:12:45.580
overview, with the European model as a base.

211
00:12:45.580 --> 00:12:48.580
I have a small advantage,

212
00:12:48.580 --> 00:12:51.740
in our region for flying

213
00:12:51.740 --> 00:12:53.740
or rather in the Alpine region,

214
00:12:53.740 --> 00:12:57.740
I really, really like to use the ICON D2 there.

215
00:12:57.740 --> 00:13:03.190
It fits the frequency very well

216
00:13:03.190 --> 00:13:06.190
and in our region,

217
00:13:06.190 --> 00:13:11.190
the forecasts really verify very well,

218
00:13:11.190 --> 00:13:13.190
not always though,

219
00:13:13.190 --> 00:13:18.700
but at least from our perspective.

220
00:13:18.700 --> 00:13:21.050
We have the infos now,

221
00:13:21.050 --> 00:13:25.340
you can dig those out and the different models,

222
00:13:25.340 --> 00:13:28.340
then you'd have to figure out for your region as well,

223
00:13:28.340 --> 00:13:31.400
by trial and error,

224
00:13:31.400 --> 00:13:38.120
what works better for you, to figure it out.

225
00:13:38.120 --> 00:13:46.840
Really, really cool — also over the whole week — is a general possibility,

226
00:13:46.840 --> 00:13:54.080
to look at the weather in a more differentiated way, so not just the wind, but in general

227
00:13:54.080 --> 00:14:02.210
an overview of everything, normally also for the region. Then there's an option

228
00:14:02.210 --> 00:14:09.430
for a specific moment that you, normally that just opens up,

229
00:14:09.430 --> 00:14:16.030
and there you've got, simply, where I see the sun, the cloud,

230
00:14:16.030 --> 00:14:22.950
the ground faded in, you've got precipitation faded in, but

231
00:14:22.950 --> 00:14:32.930
that's more for coarser forecasts. For our purposes specifically, you can

232
00:14:32.930 --> 00:14:39.090
pull up forecast meteograms, or what's actually even a bit

233
00:14:39.090 --> 00:14:46.410
better for us, because the wind, which varies with altitude, gets faded in too —

234
00:14:46.410 --> 00:15:11.450
that's the so-called airgram. So you can see there the different altitudes

235
00:15:11.450 --> 00:15:20.650
and it's actually really good and interesting. There too you can flip through the various

236
00:15:20.650 --> 00:15:28.980
models, and then you get the forecasts from those. The American model

237
00:15:28.980 --> 00:15:38.300
is the model that has been recording the longest — the most data available —

238
00:15:38.300 --> 00:15:46.100
but it also has the largest grid at 22 km, and I actually only

239
00:15:46.100 --> 00:15:54.860
use that one with care now, if I'm looking at a forecast a long way ahead, anything

240
00:15:54.860 --> 00:16:02.260
and from my perspective that's become rather inaccurate by now, and now comes

241
00:16:02.260 --> 00:16:08.540
a really cool function, the possibility — you go down here, I have

242
00:16:08.540 --> 00:16:15.260
a function selected here, that's only possible if you've taken the subscription with Windy,

243
00:16:15.260 --> 00:16:23.320
the biggest, I think 25 Euros annually, so really worth it — you have to decide for yourself

244
00:16:23.320 --> 00:16:28.220
whether 100 percent or not, but now comes a really cool function, namely you can here

245
00:16:28.880 --> 00:16:37.860
with 'compare' you can now compare all the models with one another for the corresponding day,

246
00:16:37.860 --> 00:16:48.060
that means, if practically all models forecast

247
00:16:48.060 --> 00:16:54.540
for tomorrow, we can assume that's also how it'll turn out, but if everyone

248
00:16:54.580 --> 00:17:02.640
(unclear)

249
00:17:02.640 --> 00:17:13.140
(unclear)

250
00:17:13.140 --> 00:17:14.340
(unclear)

251
00:17:14.340 --> 00:17:15.740
so

252
00:17:15.740 --> 00:17:16.620
also

253
00:17:16.640 --> 00:17:18.960
or

254
00:17:18.960 --> 00:17:25.650
also as to which models work well at the chosen location.

255
00:17:25.650 --> 00:17:32.700
But here I find another really, really cool function.

256
00:17:32.700 --> 00:17:49.370
Yeah, if you're someone with a very specific feel, who wants to analyse thermals too.

257
00:17:49.370 --> 00:17:58.820
That's a little trickier, but you really have to understand more of the emagram.

258
00:17:58.820 --> 00:18:03.080
Let me just zoom in to show how.

259
00:18:03.080 --> 00:18:10.080
And if I go here in our region onto the Drei Boden (Niederbauen), let me click into that.

260
00:18:10.080 --> 00:18:21.430
Then it pops out, okay, click, and a grid opens up with various options.

261
00:18:21.430 --> 00:18:32.440
And then you have to go all the way down to 'airology' and a function opens up for the emagram or rather,

262
00:18:32.440 --> 00:18:40.440
so to speak — and I have it set to QT down at the bottom, you can use the normal one,

263
00:18:40.440 --> 00:18:46.440
the longer normal one, or you can switch the whole thing to the other.

264
00:18:46.440 --> 00:18:51.440
So that's what I still use, the one I've learned to work with.

265
00:18:51.440 --> 00:18:58.180
And then you can actually analyse the temperature curve down there.

266
00:19:29.560 --> 00:19:38.630
Those who can or need to can at least, based on the temperature curve of the dew point,

